THE JERRY AND LARRY SHOW Fort Worth Star-Telegram American
Atheists Inc. issued a predictable boo, instead of a boo-hoo,
upon the Rev. Jerry Falwell's death Tuesday. The group called the
architect of Moral Majority "a dangerous man who opposed and
worked against many of the key values underpinning our secular
American democracy." But let's give Falwell his due: His name
stands for one of the Supreme Court's clearest pronouncements on
First Amendment guarantees. Not that it's what he intended, mind
you. But Falwell helped fortify constitutional protections for
the very parodists and satirists who loved to take his name in
vain. The case of Hustler v. Falwell surely was inspired by a
comedy writer: sanctimonious bigot Jerry versus shameless
pornmonger Larry, with a basic constitutional principle at stake.
In 1983, Hustler Publisher Larry Flynt decided to take on Falwell
through a take-off on a series of Campari liqueur ads in which
celebrities described their "first time"
